Sentiment Analysis

1. Perform a sentiment analysis using the NRC lexicon. What is the most common sentiment for each search term? What if you remove âpositiveâ and ânegativeâ from the list?

#citation for the NRC lexicon: Saif M. Mohammad and Peter Turney. (2013), ``Crowdsourcing a Word-Emotion Association Lexicon.'' Computational Intelligence, 29(3): 436-465.
#most common sentiments for each search term
pub %>%
  unnest_tokens(word, abstract) %>%
  inner_join(get_sentiments("nrc")) %>%
  group_by(term) %>%
  count(sentiment, sort = TRUE) %>%                          
  arrange(term) %>%
  slice_max(n, n = 1) %>%
  kable(caption = "Most Common Sentiment for Each Search Term",
        align = "c" )
Most Common Sentiment for Each Search Term
term sentiment n
covid positive 9874
cystic fibrosis positive 2747
meningitis negative 2109
preeclampsia positive 8014
prostate cancer negative 8918 
#Removing "positive" and "negative" sentiments from the list

pub %>%
  unnest_tokens(word, abstract) %>%
  inner_join(get_sentiments("nrc")) %>%
  group_by(term) %>%
  count(sentiment, sort = TRUE) %>%                        
  arrange(term, desc(n)) %>%
  filter(!(sentiment %in% c("positive", "negative"))) %>%  
  slice_max(n, n = 1, with_ties = FALSE) %>%                          
  kable(caption = "Most Common Sentiment for Each Search Term Without Positive or Negative", align = "c")
Most Common Sentiment for Each Search Term Without Positive or Negative

For covid, cystic fibrosis, and preclampsiaâthe top sentiments are positive, followed by fear, disgust and anticipation. For meningitis and prostate cancer, the top sentiments are negativeâfollowed by fear.

2. Now perform a sentiment analysis using the AFINN lexicon to get an average positivity score for each abstract (hint: you may want to create a variable that indexes, or counts, the abstracts). Create a visualization that shows these scores grouped by search term. Are any search terms noticeably different from the others?

# citation for the AFINN lexicon: http://www2.imm.dtu.dk/pubdb/views/publication_details.php?id=6010 
#first we create a variable that counts the abstracts and assigns an average positivity score to it
count<- pub %>%
      mutate(id = row_number())  %>%
      unnest_tokens(word, abstract)  %>%
      inner_join(get_sentiments('afinn'), by = "word")  %>%
      group_by(id, term)  %>%
      summarise(avg = mean(value, na.rm = TRUE))

# Then, we calculate the average score for each of the search terms
act<- count %>%
      group_by(term) |>
      summarise(avg_term = mean(avg, na.rm = TRUE))
act %>% kable(caption = "Average AFINN Score by Search Term", align = "c")
Average AFINN Score by Search Term
term avg_term
covid -0.1465489
cystic fibrosis 0.3223818
meningitis -0.1631295
preeclampsia -0.1210297
prostate cancer -0.2385765 
# Visualization
act <- act %>%
  mutate(type = ifelse(avg_term >= 0, "Positive", "Negative"))

act %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = term, y = avg_term)) +
  geom_col(aes(fill = type)) +
  labs(title = "Average Positivity Score Per Search Term",
       x = "Search Term",
       y = "Average AFINN Score",
       fill = "Sentiment Score Type") +
  theme_classic()

As we can see, every search term averages an overall negative AFINN score except for cystic fibrosis. While none of these have a particularly high or low score in relation to the scale, prostate cancer has the lowest score while cystic fibrosis has the highest positive sentiment score.

This is interesting because the top feeling in the NRC lexicon for covid and preclampsia are also positive, but we can see that the AFINN lexicon scores them very differently.
